{"title_page": "Daryl Hall & John Oates (album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Daryl Hall & John Oates\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Hall & Oates]]\n| cover      = Hall and Oates, Daryl Hall and John Oates (The Silver Album), 1975.png\n| alt        =\n| released   = August 18, 1975\n| recorded   = 1975\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Pop rock]], [[blue-eyed soul]]\n| length     = 35:20, 42:03 (reissue)\n| label      = [[RCA Records]]\n| producer   = Daryl Hall, John Oates, Christopher Bond\n| prev_title = [[War Babies (Hall & Oates album)|War Babies]]\n| prev_year  = 1974\n| next_title = [[Bigger Than Both of Us]]\n| next_year  = 1976\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = [[Daryl Hall & John Oates]]\n | type        = [[Album]]\n | single1     = [[Alone Too Long (song)|Alone Too Long]]\n | single1date = November 1975\n | single2     = [[Sara Smile]]\n | single2date = January 31, 1976\n}}\n}}\n\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|author=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/daryl-hall-john-oates-bonus-tracks-mw0000247712 |title=Daryl Hall & John Oates - Daryl Hall & John Oates |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2018-09-02}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Daryl Hall & John Oates''''' is the self-titled fourth [[studio album]] by American [[pop music]] duo [[Hall & Oates]]. The album was released on August 18, 1975, by [[RCA Records]]. It is sometimes referred to as '''''The Silver Album''''' because of its metallic [[glam rock]] style cover. The cover was made by Pierre LaRoche, the same artist who created [[The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars|Ziggy Stardust]] for the rock-singer [[David Bowie]]. \n\nIn 2009, Sony Music Custom Marketing Group released a triple pack of Hall & Oates albums. Along with this album, the pack included ''[[H2O (Hall & Oates album)|H2O]]'' and ''[[Ooh Yeah! (Hall & Oates album)|Ooh Yeah!]]''.\n\n==Background==\n\"Grounds for Separation\", according to [[Daryl Hall]], was going to be used in the [[Sylvester Stallone]] film ''[[Rocky]]''. [[Frank Stallone]], Sylvester's brother, had been in a band with [[John Oates]] called Valentine and this connection got them a shot at an appearance on the soundtrack. The film, however, was slow to get off the ground, and Hall and Oates withdrew the song. \"Alone Too Long\" is the theme song for the television show ''[[Hello Ladies]]'', which premiered on [[HBO]] in 2013. \"Gino (The Manager)\" is about the duo's manager at the time.  The record jacket insert reads \"And introducing [[Tommy Mottola]] as 'Little Gino.' \"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-03-04/entertainment/ca-2407_1_tommy-mottola-boyfriend-bars |title=Mottola and Music |publisher=Articles.latimes.com |date=1990-03-04 |accessdate=2018-09-02}}</ref> In 2009, the song was remixed and included on the duo's 4-CD box set ''Do What You Want, Be What You Are''.\n\nIt featured an album cover in which Daryl and John are overly made up with make-up to the point where they looked like women. Hall would later say in an interview for VH1's ''[[Behind the Music]]'' that he looked like \"the girl I always wanted to go out with\" on that album cover.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110206144855/http://www.vh1.com/video/behind-the-music-remastered/full-episodes/behind-the-music-remastered-daryl-hall-john-oates/1653842/playlist.jhtml |title=\"Behind The Music Remastered: Daryl Hall & John Oates\" ( Ep. 205 ) from Behind The Music Remastered |publisher=VH1.com |date= |accessdate=2018-09-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, [[Buddah Records]] re-released the album with two bonus tracks (\"What's Important to Me\" and \"Ice\").\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side one\n\n| title1 = Camellia\n| writer1 = [[John Oates]]\n| length1 = 2:48\n\n| title2 = [[Sara Smile]]\n| writer2 = [[Daryl Hall]], Oates\n| length2 = 3:07\n\n| title3 = [[Alone Too Long (song)|Alone Too Long]]\n| writer3 = Oates\n| length3 = 3:21 \n\n| title4 = Out of Me, Out of You\n| writer4 = Hall, Oates\n| length4 = 3:28\n\n| title5 = Nothing at All\n| writer5 = Hall, Oates\n| length5 = 4:24\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side two\n\n| title6 = Gino (The Manager)\n| writer6 = Hall, Oates\n| length6 = 4:10\n\n| title7 = (You Know) It Doesn't Matter Anymore\n| writer7 = Hall, Oates\n| length7 = 3:07\n\n| title8 = Ennui on the Mountain\n| writer8 = Hall, Oates\n| length8 = 3:15\n\n| title9 = Grounds for Separation\n| writer9 = Hall\n| length9 = 4:12\n\n| title10 = [[Soldering (song)|Soldering]]\n| writer10 = [[Ewart Beckford]], [[Alvin Ranglin]]\n| length10 = 3:24\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Remastered CD bonus tracks\n\n| title11 = What's Important to Me (Demo)\n| writer11 = Hall\n| length11 = 3:46\n\n| title12 = Ice (Demo)\n| writer12 = Oates\n| length12 = 2:57\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n* Daryl Hall \u2013 lead vocals (2, 4-10, 11), backing vocals, electric piano\n* John Oates \u2013 backing vocals, lead vocals (1, 3, 10, 12), guitars\n* Christopher Bond \u2013 synthesizer, guitars, [[Hammond organ]], horn and string arrangements, backing vocals\n* [[Clarence McDonald]] \u2013 grand piano on \"Sara Smile\"\n* Scott Edwards \u2013 bass\n* [[Leland Sklar]] \u2013 bass\n* [[Jim Gordon (musician)|Jim Gordon]] \u2013 drums\n* [[Ed Greene]] \u2013 drums\n* [[Mike Baird (musician)|Mike Baird]] \u2013 drums on \"Grounds for Separation\"\n* Gary Coleman \u2013 percussion\n* [[Sara Allen|Sandy Allen]] \u2013 backing vocals on \"(You Know) It Doesn't Matter Anymore\"\n\n==Production==\n* Produced by Christopher Bond, Daryl Hall and John Oates.\n* Engineered by [[Barry Rudolph]]\n* Strings and horns engineered by Armin Steiner\n* Recorded at [[Larrabee Sound Studios|Larrabee Sound Studio]]<nowiki/>s (North Hollywood, CA) and Western Sound Recorders (Los Angeles, CA).\n* Mixed by Christopher Bond and [[Barry Rudolph]] at Sound Labs (Hollywood, CA).\n* Mastered by Allen Zentz at Allen Zentz Mastering (San Clemente, CA).\n* A&R Coordination \u2013 Margie Meoli\n* Make-up and Cover Concept \u2013 Pierre LaRoche\n* Photography \u2013 [[Bill King (photographer)|Bill King]]\n;2000 Reissue\n* Producers \u2013 Jeremy Holiday and Rob Santos\n* Editing and Mixing \u2013 Dennis Ferrante\n* Mastering \u2013 Elliott Federman\n* Digital Transfers Technician \u2013 Bob Harty\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Hall & Oates}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Daryl Hall and John Oates (album)}}\n[[Category:1975 albums]]\n[[Category:Hall & Oates albums]]\n[[Category:RCA Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Daryl Hall & John Oates\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Hall & Oates]]\n| cover      = Hall and Oates, Daryl Hall and John Oates (The Silver Album), 1975.png\n| alt        =\n| released   = August 18, 1975\n| recorded   = 1975\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Pop rock]], [[blue-eyed soul]]\n| length     = 35:20, 42:03 (reissue)\n| label      = [[RCA Records]]\n| producer   = Daryl Hall, John Oates, Christopher Bond\n| prev_title = [[War Babies (Hall & Oates album)|War Babies]]\n| prev_year  = 1974\n| next_title = [[Bigger Than Both of Us]]\n| next_year  = 1976\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = [[Daryl Hall & John Oates]]\n | type        = [[Album]]\n | single1     = [[Alone Too Long (song)|Alone Too Long]]\n | single1date = November 1975\n | single2     = [[Sara Smile]]\n | single2date = January 31, 1976\n}}\n}}\n\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|author=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/daryl-hall-john-oates-bonus-tracks-mw0000247712 |title=Daryl Hall & John Oates - Daryl Hall & John Oates |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2018-09-02}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Daryl Hall & John Oates''''' is the self-titled fourth [[studio album]] by American [[pop music]] duo [[Hall & Oates]]. The album was released on August 18, 1975, by [[RCA Records]]. It is sometimes referred to as '''''The Silver Album''''' because of its metallic [[glam rock]] style cover. The cover was made by Pierre LaRoche, the same artist who created [[The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars|Ziggy Stardust]] for the rock-singer [[David Bowie]]. \n\nIn 2009, Sony Music Custom Marketing Group released a triple pack of Hall & Oates albums. Along with this album, the pack included ''[[H2O (Hall & Oates album)|H2O]]'' and ''[[Ooh Yeah! (Hall & Oates album)|Ooh Yeah!]]''.\n\n==Background==\n\"Grounds for Separation\", according to [[Daryl Hall]], was going to be used in the [[Sylvester Stallone]] film ''[[Rocky]]''. [[Frank Stallone]], Sylvester's brother, had been in a band with [[John Oates]] called Valentine and this connection got them a shot at an appearance on the soundtrack. The film, however, was slow to get off the ground, and Hall and Oates withdrew the song. \"Alone Too Long\" is the theme song for the television show ''[[Hello Ladies]]'', which premiered on [[HBO]] in 2013. \"Gino (The Manager)\" is about the duo's manager at the time.  The record jacket insert reads \"And introducing [[Tommy Mottola]] as 'Little Gino.' \"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-03-04/entertainment/ca-2407_1_tommy-mottola-boyfriend-bars |title=Mottola and Music |publisher=Articles.latimes.com |date=1990-03-04 |accessdate=2018-09-02}}</ref> In 2009, the song was remixed and included on the duo's 4-CD box set ''Do What You Want, Be What You Are''.\n\nIt featured an album cover in which Daryl and John are overly made up with make-up to the point where they looked like women. Hall would later say in an interview for VH1's ''[[Behind the Music]]'' that he looked like \"the girl I always wanted to go out with\" on that album cover.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110206144855/http://www.vh1.com/video/behind-the-music-remastered/full-episodes/behind-the-music-remastered-daryl-hall-john-oates/1653842/playlist.jhtml |title=\"Behind The Music Remastered: Daryl Hall & John Oates\" ( Ep. 205 ) from Behind The Music Remastered |publisher=VH1.com |date= |accessdate=2018-09-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, [[Buddah Records]] re-released the album with two bonus tracks (\"What's Important to Me\" and \"Ice\").\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side one\n\n| title1 = Camellia\n| writer1 = [[John Oates]]\n| length1 = 2:48\n\n| title2 = [[Sara Smile]]\n| writer2 = [[Daryl Hall]], Oates\n| length2 = 3:07\n\n| title3 = [[Alone Too Long (song)|Alone Too Long]]\n| writer3 = Oates\n| length3 = 3:21 \n\n| title4 = Out of Me, Out of You\n| writer4 = Hall, Oates\n| length4 = 3:28\n\n| title5 = Nothing at All\n| writer5 = Hall, Oates\n| length5 = 4:24\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side two\n\n| title6 = Gino (The Manager)\n| writer6 = Hall, Oates\n| length6 = 4:10\n\n| title7 = (You Know) It Doesn't Matter Anymore\n| writer7 = Hall, Oates\n| length7 = 3:07\n\n| title8 = Ennui on the Mountain\n| writer8 = Hall, Oates\n| length8 = 3:15\n\n| title9 = Grounds for Separation\n| writer9 = Hall\n| length9 = 4:12\n\n| title10 = [[Soldering (song)|Soldering]]\n| writer10 = [[Ewart Beckford]], [[Alvin Ranglin]]\n| length10 = 3:24\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Remastered CD bonus tracks\n\n| title11 = What's Important to Me (Demo)\n| writer11 = Hall\n| length11 = 3:46\n\n| title12 = Ice (Demo)\n| writer12 = Oates\n| length12 = 2:57\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n* Daryl Hall \u2013 lead vocals (2, 4-10, 11), backing vocals, electric piano\n* John Oates \u2013 backing vocals, lead vocals (1, 3, 10, 12), guitars\n* Christopher Bond \u2013 synthesizer, guitars, [[Hammond organ]], horn and string arrangements, backing vocals\n* [[Clarence McDonald]] \u2013 grand piano on \"Sara Smile\"\n* Scott Edwards \u2013 bass\n* [[Leland Sklar]] \u2013 bass\n* [[Jim Gordon (musician)|Jim Gordon]] \u2013 drums\n* [[Ed Greene]] \u2013 drums\n* [[Mike Baird (musician)|Mike Baird]] \u2013 drums on \"Grounds for Separation\"\n* Gary Coleman \u2013 percussion\n* [[Sara Allen|Sandy Allen]] \u2013 backing vocals on \"(You Know) It Doesn't Matter Anymore\"\n\n==Production==\n* Produced by Christopher Bond, Daryl Hall and John Oates.\n* Engineered by Barry Rudolph\n* Strings and horns engineered by Armin Steiner\n* Recorded at Larrabee Sound Studio (North Hollywood, CA) and Western Sound Recorders (Los Angeles, CA).\n* Mixed by Christopher Bond and Barry Rudolph at Sound Labs (Hollywood, CA).\n* Mastered by Allen Zentz at Allen Zentz Mastering (San Clemente, CA).\n* A&R Coordination \u2013 Margie Meoli\n* Make-up and Cover Concept \u2013 Pierre LaRoche\n* Photography \u2013 [[Bill King (photographer)|Bill King]]\n;2000 Reissue\n* Producers \u2013 Jeremy Holiday and Rob Santos\n* Editing and Mixing \u2013 Dennis Ferrante\n* Mastering \u2013 Elliott Federman\n* Digital Transfers Technician \u2013 Bob Harty\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Hall & Oates}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Daryl Hall and John Oates (album)}}\n[[Category:1975 albums]]\n[[Category:Hall & Oates albums]]\n[[Category:RCA Records albums]]\n", "name_user": "TanookiKoopa", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added links to Barry Rudolph and Larrabee Sound", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daryl_Hall_%26_John_Oates_(album)"}
