{"title_page": "William Brant", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name          = William Brant\n|image         = \n|birth_date    = 1840 <!--{{birth date|yyyy|mm|dd}}-->\n|death_date    = March 2, 1898 <!--{{death date and age|1898|03|02|yyyy|mm|dd}}-->\n|birth_place   = [[Elizabeth, New Jersey]]\n|death_place   = [[New Jersey]]\n|placeofburial = [[Evergreen Cemetery, Hillside]]\n|allegiance    ={{flag|United States of America|1861}}\n|branch        ={{army|USA}}\n|serviceyears  = 1861 - 1865\n|rank          = [[Captain (United States)|Captain]]\n|unit          = {{Flagicon|New Jersey}} [[1st Regiment New Jersey Volunteer Infantry]] - Company B\n|battles       = [[Third Battle of Petersburg]]\n|awards        = {{Flagicon image|Medal of Honor ribbon.svg}} [[Medal of Honor]]\n}}\n\n'''William Brant, Jr.''' (1840 to March 2, 1898<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://projects.militarytimes.com/citations-medals-awards/recipient.php?recipientid=3129 |title=William Brant, Jr. |accessdate=9 October 2013}}</ref>) was an [[United States|American]] soldier who fought in the [[American Civil War]]. Brant received the country's highest award for bravery during combat, the [[Medal of Honor]], for his action at Petersburg, [[Virginia]] on 3 April 1865. He was honored with the award on 10 May 1865.<ref name=\"History\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.history.army.mil/moh/civilwar_af.html |title=Civil War (A-L) Medal of Honor Recipients |accessdate=25 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Valor\">{{Cite web |url=http://valor.defense.gov/Recipients/ArmyMedalofHonorRecipients.aspx |title=U.S. Army Medal of Honor Recipients |accessdate=9 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nBrant joined the [[1st New Jersey Volunteer Infantry]] in May 1861, and was commissioned as an officer in February 1865. He mustered out with his regiment in June 1865.<ref>[http://www.njdept-suvcw.org/pdf_files/nj_medal_of_honor_recipients.pdf NJ Medal of Honor recipients]</ref>\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\n{{quotation|Capture of battle flag of 46th North Carolina (C.S.A.).<ref name=\"History\"/>}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A\u2013F]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brant, William}}\n[[Category:1840 births]]\n[[Category:1898 deaths]]\n[[Category:People of New Jersey in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n[[Category:Burials at Evergreen Cemetery, Hillside, New Jersey]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name          = William Brant\n|image         = \n|birth_date    = 1840 <!--{{birth date|yyyy|mm|dd}}-->\n|death_date    = March 2, 1898 <!--{{death date and age|1898|03|02|yyyy|mm|dd}}-->\n|birth_place   = [[Elizabeth, New Jersey]]\n|death_place   = [[New Jersey]]\n|placeofburial = [[Evergreen Cemetery, Hillside]]\n|allegiance    ={{flag|United States of America|1861}}\n|branch        ={{army|USA}}\n|serviceyears  = 1861 - 1865\n|rank          = [[Captain (United States)|Captain]]\n|unit          = {{Flagicon|New Jersey}} Company B, [[1st New Jersey Volunteer Infantry]]\n|battles       = [[Third Battle of Petersburg]]\n|awards        = {{Flagicon image|Medal of Honor ribbon.svg}} [[Medal of Honor]]\n}}\n\n'''William Brant, Jr.''' (1840 to March 2, 1898<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://projects.militarytimes.com/citations-medals-awards/recipient.php?recipientid=3129 |title=William Brant, Jr. |accessdate=9 October 2013}}</ref>) was an [[United States|American]] soldier who fought in the [[American Civil War]]. Brant received the country's highest award for bravery during combat, the [[Medal of Honor]], for his action at Petersburg, [[Virginia]] on 3 April 1865. He was honored with the award on 10 May 1865.<ref name=\"History\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.history.army.mil/moh/civilwar_af.html |title=Civil War (A-L) Medal of Honor Recipients |accessdate=25 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Valor\">{{Cite web |url=http://valor.defense.gov/Recipients/ArmyMedalofHonorRecipients.aspx |title=U.S. Army Medal of Honor Recipients |accessdate=9 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nBrant joined the [[1st New Jersey Volunteer Infantry]] in May 1861, and was commissioned as an officer in February 1865. He mustered out with his regiment in June 1865.<ref>[http://www.njdept-suvcw.org/pdf_files/nj_medal_of_honor_recipients.pdf NJ Medal of Honor recipients]</ref>\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\n{{quotation|Capture of battle flag of 46th North Carolina (C.S.A.).<ref name=\"History\"/>}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A\u2013F]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brant, William}}\n[[Category:1840 births]]\n[[Category:1898 deaths]]\n[[Category:People of New Jersey in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n[[Category:Burials at Evergreen Cemetery, Hillside, New Jersey]]\n", "name_user": "Hhfjbaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Brant"}
{"title_page": "Smoked meat", "text_new": "{{short description|Type of prepared meat}}\n{{For|the general process|Smoking (cooking)}}\n{{Infobox food\n| name             = Smoked meat\n| image            = O Piornedo, Don\u00eds, Cervantes 10.jpg\n| image_size       = 300px\n| caption          = Smoked meats\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = \n| region           = \n| creator          = \n| course           = \n| type             = Meat or fish\n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = [[red meat]], [[white meat]], [[fish]], [[spices]], smoke\n| variations       = \n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n\n[[File:Chambre de boucanage.jpg|thumb|17th-century diagram for a [[smokehouse]] for producing smoked meat]]\n\n'''Smoked meat''' is the result of a method of preparing [[red meat]], [[white meat]], and [[seafood]] which originated in the [[Paleolithic|Paleolithic Era]]. Smoking adds [[flavor]], improves the appearance of meat through the [[Maillard reaction]], and combined with [[Curing (food preservation)|curing]] [[Food preservation|preserves]] the meat.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Huang|first=Huisuo|date=2016|title=APPLICATIONS OF LACTIC ACID AND ITS DERIVATIVES IN MEAT PRODUCTS AND METHODS...|url=https://mospace.umsystem.edu/xmlui/bitstream/handle/10355/57183/research.pdf?sequence=2&isAllowed=y|journal=Thesis|via=University of Missouri-Columbia}}</ref> When meat is cured then cold-smoked, the smoke adds [[phenols]] and other chemicals that have an [[antimicrobial]] effect on the meat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pods.dasnr.okstate.edu/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-2055/ANSI-3994web.pdf|title=Meat Curing|last=Ray|first=Frederick|website=Oklahoma State University|publisher=Oklahoma Cooperative Extension Service|access-date=July 24, 2019}}</ref> Hot smoking has less impact on preservation and is primarily used for taste and to slow-cook the meat.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.canr.msu.edu/news/smoking_as_a_food_cooking_method|title=Smoking as a food cooking method|website=MSU Extension|language=en|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref> Interest in [[barbecue]] and smoking is on the rise worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/food/move-over-foie-gras-the-latest-rage-in-paris-is--classic-american-barbecue/2016/01/15/1b3ff700-ba52-11e5-829c-26ffb874a18d_story.html|title=Move over, foie gras: The latest rage in Paris is . . . classic American barbecue|website=Washington Post|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hpba.org/Resources/PressRoom/ID/516/2017-State-of-the-Barbecue-Industry-HPBAs-Consumer-Survey-Reveals-Grilling-and-Barbecuing-Is-a-Growing-Year-Round-Lifestyle|title=2017 State of the Barbecue Industry: HPBA's Consumer Survey Reveals Grilling and Barbecuing Is a Growing, Year-Round Lifestyle > Hearth, Patio & Barbecue Association (HPBA)|website=www.hpba.org|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref>\n\n==Smoking with wood==\n\nGenerally wood is [[Smoking (cooking)|smoked]] using [[hardwood]] or [[Pellet fuel|wood pellets]] made from hardwood, softwood is not recommended due to increased PAH from the resin.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Ezike|first=C.O.|date=2018|title=Hydrocarbons (Pahs) in Hardwood and Softwood - Smoked Fish|url=|journal=Journal of Animal Science|volume=2|issue=1|pages=1012|via=JSTOR}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wideopeneats.com/kind-wood-use-smoking-meat/|title=Every Type of Wood to Use for Smoking Every Type of Meat|last=Mattison|first=Lindsay|date=2018-03-27|website=Wide Open Eats|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> Wood smoke adds [[flavor]], [[aroma]], and helps with [[Food preservation|preservation]].<ref name=\":4\" /> There are two types of smoking: cold smoking generally occurs below {{Convert|90|F|C|abbr=}} and has more preservative value. Hot smoking generally occurs above {{Convert|160|F|C}}.<ref name=\":22\" /> Most woods are [[Wood drying|seasoned]] and not used [[Green wood|green]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bbq.tamu.edu/2016/01/07/seasoned-wood-for-smoking-barbecue/|title=Importance of seasoned wood for smoking barbecue|last=Savell|first=Jeff|date=2016-01-07|website=Texas Barbecue|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-27}}</ref> There are many types of wood used for smoking; a partial list includes:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thespruceeats.com/choose-right-wood-barbecue-smoke-331529|title=Choose the Right Wood for Your Smoker|website=The Spruce Eats|language=en|access-date=2019-07-27}}</ref>\n\n* Woods with a mild flavor: [[Alder]], [[apple]], [[apricot]], [[Fraxinus|ash]], [[birch]], [[cherry]], [[maple]], [[peach]], [[pear]].\n* Woods with a medium flavor: [[Almond]], [[hickory]], [[pecan]], [[Quercus stellata|post oak]], [[Lithocarpus|pasania]].\n* Woods with a strong flavor: [[Acacia]], [[Juglans nigra|black walnut]], [[Prunus virginiana|chokecherry]], [[Vitis|grapevine]], [[mesquite]].\n* Other woods and organic matter: [[Avocado]], [[Laurus nobilis|bay]], [[beech]], [[Juglans cinerea|butternut]], [[Cupaniopsis anacardioides|carrotwood]], [[camphor]], [[castanopsis]], [[chestnut]], [[Thyine wood|citrus woods]], [[Populus|cottonwood]], [[Malus|crabapple]], [[Ficus|fig]], [[guava]], [[Eucalyptus|gum]], [[Celtis|hackberry]], [[Prosopis pallida|kiawe]], [[Syringa vulgaris|lilac]], [[Arbutus|madrone]], [[Morus (plant)|mulberry]], [[olive]], [[peat]], [[plum]], [[persimmon]], [[Allspice|pimento]], [[Camellia sinensis|tea]], and [[willow]].\n\n==Types==\n===African fish smoking===\n[[File:Smoking fish near Dakar, S\u00e9n\u00e9gal (west Africa) (2290515874).jpg|thumb|Smoking fish near Dakar, S\u00e9n\u00e9gal]]\nClose to 80% of all fish caught in most [[African nations]] is [[Smoked fish|smoked]].<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Adeyeye|first=S. A. O.|last2=Oyewole|first2=O. B.|date=2016|title=An Overview of Traditional Fish Smoking In Africa|journal=Journal of Culinary Science & Technology|volume=14|issue=3|pages=198\u2013215|via=JSTOR|doi=10.1080/15428052.2015.1102785}}</ref> Traditionally the processing and smoking of fish has been done by women.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldfishcenter.org/sites/default/files/u24/Annex-26-Guidelines-for-Orientation-and-Training-on-Standards---Processors-and-Traders-Module.pdf|title=Methodologies and Guidelines for Training/ Orientation on Standards to Non-Standards Experts and Cross-Border Trade Compliance|last=|first=|date=|website=World Fish|publisher=World Fish & ARSO|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=August 1, 2019}}</ref> The primary method of smoking is [[Hot-smoking|hot smoking]], the flavor from hot smoking preferred by local consumers.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite journal|last=Tall|first=Amadou|date=5 November 1976|title=OBSTACLES TO THE DEVELOPMENT OF SMALL SCALE FISH TRADE IN WEST AFRICA|url=https://www.oceandocs.org/bitstream/handle/1834/745/Infopeche.pdf?sequence=1|journal=Infopeche|publisher=Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Traditional smoking methods include using bamboo racks over smoky fires, mud ovens and placing the fish directly on smoldering woods and grasses.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":9\" /> Modern methods of smoking include using re-purposed [[oil drums]], [[brick oven]]s, and [[Chorkor oven]]s.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n===American barbecue (smoked)===\n[[File:Smoking Meat.jpg|thumb|American barbecue]]\n{{main|Barbecue}}American [[Barbecue in the United States|barbecue]]'s roots start with the [[Native American cuisine|Native Americans]] who [[smoked fish]] and game to preserve food for leaner times.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bennet|first=M K|date=October 1955|title=The Food Economy of the New England Indians, 1605-75|journal=The Journal of Political Economy|publisher=The University of Chicago Press|volume=LXIII|issue=5|pages=369\u2013397|via=JSTOR}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Driver|first=Harold|last2=Massey|first2=William|date=1957|title=Comparative Studies of North American Indians|journal=Transactions of the American Philosophical Society|publisher=American Philosophical Society|volume=47|issue=2|pages=165 456|doi=10.2307/1005714|jstor=1005714|hdl=2027/mdp.39015000051691|hdl-access=free}}</ref> When [[European colonization of the Americas|Europeans]] first came to North America, they brought with them smoking techniques from Europe and [[Central Asia]] and combined those with the Native American techniques.<ref name=\":22\" /> American barbecue has distinct regional differences: [[North Carolina]] Piedmont style is [[pork shoulder]] with a vinegar & ketchup-based sauce; Eastern style is the whole hog with vinegar & pepper-based sauce; [[South Carolina]] is whole hog or shoulder with a mustard-based sauce; [[Western Tennessee]] and [[Memphis barbeque|Memphis]] are famous for its [[dry rub]] ribs, but wet is also available; [[Kentucky]] is known for their [[mutton]], pork shoulder and whole hog are also very popular; [[Kansas City]] barbecue is more about the [[Barbecue sauce|sauce]], often used with smoked pork, [[lamb and mutton|lamb]], [[chicken]], [[beef]] and [[turkey as food|turkey]]. [[Beef rib]]s, [[Sausage|smoked sausage]], [[Beef brisket|brisket]] are the prevalent meats in Texas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eater.com/2016/6/16/11889444/where-to-eat-barbecue-styles|title=The American Barbecue Regional Style Guide|last=Solares|first=Nick|date=2016-06-16|website=Eater|access-date=2019-07-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://libraries.mercer.edu/ursa/bitstream/handle/10898/1520/Barbecue%20project.pdf;sequence=5|title=Adaptations of Barbecue|last=Bove|first=A.|last2=Drawdy|first2=J.|website=Mercer University|last3=Mitchell|first3=D.|last4=Moye|first4=L.|last5=Thompson|first5=S.|last6=Turnquist|first6=T.|last7=Wagner|authorlink7=M.}}</ref>\n\n===Bacon===\n[[File:American Bacon.jpg|thumb|American \"streaky\" bacon]]\n{{main|Bacon}}Bacon originated with ''petaso'', a Roman version of what is now called bacon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inc.com/john-boitnott/why-bacon-as-a-business-has-no-end-in-sight.html|title=The Bacon Craze Will Never End|last=Boitnott|first=John|date=2014-08-08|website=Inc.com|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> The [[etymology]] of the word ''bacon'' has four possibilities; the [[Old French|Franceis]] word ''bacon'', the [[Old High German|Althochdeutsch]] word ''bahho'', the [[Old Dutch|Old Low Franconian]] word ''baken'', and the [[Proto-Germanic language|Common Germanic]] word ''bakkon''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.englishbreakfastsociety.com/history-of-bacon.html|title=The History of Bacon|last=Bule|first=Guise|date=2018|website=The English Breakfast Society}}</ref> John Harris of [[Calne|Calne, England]], was the first to commercialize production of bacon in the 1770s.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://englishbreakfastsociety.com/history-of-bacon.html|title=History Of Bacon|website=English Breakfast Society|access-date=July 28, 2019}}</ref> Bacon is primarily [[pork]], depending on the type; it can come from the belly, back, loin or side.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rhssilverscribe.org/2459/features/history-of-bacon/|title=History of Bacon|last=Adamson|first=Brynne|website=The Silver Scribe|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> The preparation of bacon varies by type, but most involve [[curing (food preservation)|curing]] and smoking.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://meatscience.org/TheMeatWeEat/topics/processed-meats/article/2017/09/07/bacon---do-you-know-how-it-is-made|title=Bacon - Do you know how it is made?|website=meatscience.org|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> Some of the types of bacon include American ({{a.k.a.}} side bacon or streaky bacon), buckboard (shoulder bacon), Canadian ([[back bacon]]), British and Irish (rasher), Australian (middle bacon), Italian ([[pancetta]]), Hungarian ([[Szalonna (bacon)|szalonna]]), German ([[speck]]), Japanese (beikon), and Slovakian (oravsk\u00e1).<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.oola.com/life-in-flavor/2476027/17-types-of-bacon-you-probably-havent-tried-yet/|title=17 Types of Bacon You Probably Haven't Tried Yet|date=2019-07-03|website=Oola.com|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailymeal.com/travel/ways-bacon-eaten-around-world-0/slide-2|title=Australia from 13 Ways People Eat Bacon Around the World Gallery|website=The Daily Meal|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> Bacon can also be produced from beef, lamb, and [[wild game]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.therecipe.com/different-kinds-bacon-around-the-world/|title=20 Different Kinds Of Bacon From Around The World|date=2018-11-05|website=TheRecipe|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n\n===Country ham===\n{{main|Country ham}}\n[[File:Country ham.jpg|thumb|Country ham]]\n[[Country ham]] is a popular ham originally developed by [[Thirteen Colonies|American Colonists]] who took traditional Native American fish smoking practices and used them for pork.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1979/09/23/country-hams-well-worth-their-salt-ham-thats-worth-its-salt/5f7d16d1-e7c1-45cb-8416-5d0e9dafe467/|title=The Washington Post|last=Northrop|first=Jo|work=September 23, 1979|access-date=July 25, 2019}}</ref> Country hams traditionally were made in the [[American Southeast]] from [[Virginia]] to [[Missouri]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Rentfrow|first=Greg|last2=Suman|first2=Surendranath|date=2014|title=How to Make a Country Ha|journal=Agriculture and Natural Resources Publications|volume=145|via=JSTOR}}</ref> Most country hams are trimmed, wrapped, [[Cured ham|cured]] in salt, sugar, pepper and various spices. In modern times, some preparations add [[nitrate]]s for [[food safety]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eater.com/2014/10/29/7080059/feature-newsoms-country-hams|title=Ghosts in the Ham House|last=Sula|first=Mike|date=2014-10-29|website=Eater|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref> After curing the hams are smoked for at least 12 hours, then hung to dry for 9 to 12 months. Some traditional processes can take years from curing to being ready to consume.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Marshall|first=Howard|date=1979|title=Meat Preservation on the Farm in Missouri's \"Little Dixie\"|journal=Journal of American Folklore|volume=92|issue=366|via=JSTOR}}</ref>\n\n===Finnan haddie===\n[[File:FMIB 38894 Smoking Finnan Haddie.jpeg|thumb|Smoking Finnan haddie]]\n{{main|Finnan haddie}}[[Finnan haddie]] is a [[Smoking (cooking)|cold smoked]] [[haddock]] that originated in medieval times in the Scottish village of [[Findon, West Sussex|Findon]].<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Hopley|first=Claire|date=September 1997|title=FINNAN HADDIE|journal=British Heritage|volume=18|issue=6|pages=56|via=EBCO}}</ref> Traditionally the haddock is smoked with [[green wood]] and [[peat]].<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://slowfoodscotland.com/ark-of-taste/|title=Slow Food Scotland - Ark of Taste|language=en|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref> Smoked finnan haddie is the colour of [[straw]], newer commercial methods of drying without smoke produce a  gold or yellow colour.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> Until the 1800s when regular rail service was established, finnan haddie remained a local dish, now it can be found in markets worldwide.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n===Katsuobushi===\n[[File:\u67af\u672c\u80cc\u7bc0 (8517415760).jpg|thumb|Katsuobushi]]\n{{main|Katsuobushi}}[[Katsuobushi]] is a key [[umami]] ingredient in [[Japanese cuisine]], with bonito flakes among its many applications.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://japanology.org/2017/04/the-8-most-important-condiments-and-ingredients-in-japanese-cuisine/|title=The 8 Most Important Condiments and Ingredients in Japanese cuisine|date=2017-04-18|website=Japanology|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> Katsuobushi is made from [[Skipjack tuna|skipjack]] tuna that is washed, quartered smoked with [[oak]], pasania, or castanopsis wood, and cooled repeatedly for a month.<ref>{{Citation|last=Travis Wall|title=Japanology Plus 2016 12 0 Katsuobushi|date=2017-04-28|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MbX9fq5M_pk|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> Some producers will spray the fish with [[Aspergillus glaucus]] to promote further drying.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hesseltine|first=C. W.|date=1965|title=A Millennium of Fungi, Food, and Fermentation|journal=Mycologia|volume=57|issue=2|pages=149\u2013197|via=JSTOR|doi=10.1080/00275514.1965.12018201}}</ref> After one to 24 months the fish will be katsu (hard) and read for use. To make bonito flakes it is shaved very thin using a Katsuobushi grater box.\n\n===Pastrami===\n[[File:Pastrami by Wise Sons. (14519474073).jpg|thumb|Pastrami]]\n{{main|Pastrami}}[[Pastrami]] is most often made with beef [[brisket]]; it can be made with other cuts of beef.<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite journal|last=Benkerroum|first=Noreddine|title=Traditional Fermented Foods of North African Countries: Technology and Food Safety Challenges With Regard to Microbiological Risks|url=https://www.academia.edu/25785321|journal=Comprehensive Reviews in Food Science and Food Safety|language=en|volume=12|issue=1|pages=54\u201389|issn=1541-4337|doi=10.1111/j.1541-4337.2012.00215.x|year=2013}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite book|title=Umami : unlocking the secrets of the fifth taste|last=Mouritsen, Ole G., author.|isbn=9780231168915|oclc=932317386|date = 2015-01-11}}</ref> The meat is cured in a [[brine]] (most often dry), after drying, it is coated in [[spice]]s and smoked.<ref name=\":12\" /> Smoking can be done by either cold smoking or hot smoking.<ref name=\":12\" /> Pastrami evolved from the [[Huns|Turkish Huns]] who would tenderize and dry meat under their saddles.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nurten|first=Cekal|date=2014|title=Traditional Foods in Turkish Cuisine|journal=The Social Sciences|volume=9|issue=1|pages=1\u20136|via=JSTOR}}</ref> [[Armenians]] saw what the Huns had done and created [[Pastirma|basturma]] that was spiced and air-dried meat.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite journal|last=Durham|first=T. R.|date=2001-02-01|title=Salt, Smoke, and History|url=https://gcfs.ucpress.edu/content/1/1/78|journal=Gastronomica: The Journal of Critical Food Studies|language=en|volume=1|issue=1|pages=78\u201382|issn=1529-3262|doi=10.1525/gfc.2001.1.1.78}}</ref> [[Romanians]] first started brining, spicing, and smoking the beef and created what is now called pastrami.<ref name=\":22\" /> When [[Romanian Jews]] immigrated to the United States, Canada, and Great Britain in the late 1800s, they carried that tradition of pastrami with them.<ref name=\":22\" /> The Romanians that immigrated to the United States, mostly settled in [[New York City]] area and developed the classic New York Pastrami.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://unreachednewyork.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/Romanian-Profile-Final.pdf|title=Romanians in the New York Metro Area|last=All Peoples|first=Initiative|date=July 2009|website=Unreached New York|access-date=July 24, 2019}}</ref> Those that immigrated to Canada mostly settled in [[Montreal]] used a different brining technique and spices and called it [[Montreal-style smoked meat|smoked meat]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Cured, fermented and smoked foods : proceedings of the Oxford Symposium on Food and Cookery 2010|last=Saberi, Helen.|date=2011|publisher=Prospect Books|isbn=9781903018859|oclc=767899626}}</ref> Pastrami is still produced in [[Southwest Asia]] and the [[Middle East]] and is called [[Pastirma|Pastirma, basterma or basturma]].<ref name=\":03\" /> While customarily made with beef, in other regions it can be made with lamb, [[goat]], [[Water buffalo|buffalo]], and [[camel]].<ref name=\":03\" /> [[Corned beef|Corned or salt beef]] uses a similar brine and spices, but is not smoked.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\n===Zhangcha duck===\n[[File:Zhangcha tea smoked duck.jpg|thumb|Zhangcha duck]]\n{{main|Zhangcha duck}}[[Zhangcha duck]] is a dish from [[Sichuan cuisine|Sichuan]] Province in southwestern China made from the Chengdu Ma duck.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unesco.org/new/fileadmin/MULTIMEDIA/HQ/CLT/pdf/CNN_Chengdu_Application_Gastronomy_EN.pdf|title=Chengdu's Application to Join the UNESCO Creative Cities Network as a City of Gastronomy|date=February 2008|website=The United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization}}</ref> The duck is [[Marination|marinated]] in a [[Pickling|pickling liquid]] then smoked with [[Camphorosmeae|camphor]] and tea leaves.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.weiwenku.org/d/104298982|title=Sichuan Cuisine and Snakes \u56db\u5ddd\u83dc\u8207\u5c0f\u5403|website=\u4e2d\u570b\u50b3\u7d71\u6587\u5316\u8a5e\u5f59 (Chinese traditional culture vocabulary)|access-date=27 July 2019}}</ref> After smoking the duck is [[Deep frying|deep fried]], boned and served over [[rice]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Health concerns==\nOne study has shown an association between the frequency of consumption of smoked foods and [[intestinal cancer]].<ref name=\"Fritz\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Fritz | first1 = W. | last2 = So\u00f3s | first2 = K. | title = Smoked food and cancer | journal = Bibliotheca Nutritio et Dieta | volume = 29 | issue = 29 | pages = 57\u201364 | year = 1980 | pmid = 7447916| doi = 10.1159/000387467 | series = Forum of Nutrition | isbn = 978-3-8055-0621-2 }}</ref> However, the study was restricted to a small Slovenian population in Hungary, where the local smoke curing process produces levels of contaminants roughly eight times as high as standard processes elsewhere.<ref name=\"Fritz\" /> Smoked meats have the potential for promoting the growth of ''[[Listeria]]'' bacteria. ''[[Listeria monocytogenes]]'' can also cause serious [[neonatal infection]] and can be [[vertical transmission|transmitted from mother to child]] before or after birth. The infection can cause serious harm or even [[infant mortality|infant death]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Listeria (Listeriosis) |publisher= Centers for Disease Control and Prevention| url = https://www.cdc.gov/listeria/index.html | date= 22 October 2015| accessdate = 2015-12-23}}</ref> The use of soft woods is discouraged, as the resins in softwood increases the concentration of [[polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon]]s (PAHs) that are known carcinogens.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Cooking|Food}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[African longfin eel]]\n* [[Atlantic mackerel]]\n* [[Beef jerky]]\n* [[Black Forest ham]]\n* [[Br\u00e9si]]\n* [[Cod as food|Cod]]\n* [[Cecina (meat)|Cecina]]\n* [[Charcuterie]]\n* [[Deli meat]]\n* [[Gammon (meat)|Gammon]]\n* [[Herring as food|Herring]]\n* [[List of smoked foods]]\n* [[Smoked salmon|Salmon]]\n* [[Suho meso]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{commons category-inline|Smoked meat}}\n* {{Cookbook-inline|Smoking}}\n* [https://www.stevenraichlen.com/programs/project-smoke/ Project Smoke]\n\n{{Meat}}\n\n[[Category:Smoked meat| ]]\n[[Category:Jewish cuisine]]\n[[Category:Louisiana cuisine]]\n[[Category:Cold cut]]\n[[Category:Sandwiches]]\n[[Category:Montreal cuisine]]\n[[Category:Cuisine of Quebec]]\n[[Category:Canadian cuisine]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Type of prepared meat}}\n{{For|the general process|Smoking (cooking)}}\n{{Infobox food\n| name             = Smoked meat\n| image            = O Piornedo, Don\u00eds, Cervantes 10.jpg\n| image_size       = 300px\n| caption          = Smoked meats\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = \n| region           = \n| creator          = \n| course           = \n| type             = Meat or fish\n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = [[red meat]], [[white meat]], [[fish]], [[spices]], smoke\n| variations       = \n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n\n[[File:Chambre de boucanage.jpg|thumb|17th-century diagram for a [[smokehouse]] for producing smoked meat]]\n\n'''Smoked meat''' is the result of a method of preparing [[red meat]], [[white meat]], and [[seafood]] which originated in the [[Paleolithic|Paleolithic Era]]. Smoking adds [[flavor]], improves the appearance of meat through the [[Maillard reaction]], and combined with [[Curing (food preservation)|curing]] [[Food preservation|preserves]] the meat.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Huang|first=Huisuo|date=2016|title=APPLICATIONS OF LACTIC ACID AND ITS DERIVATIVES IN MEAT PRODUCTS AND METHODS...|url=https://mospace.umsystem.edu/xmlui/bitstream/handle/10355/57183/research.pdf?sequence=2&isAllowed=y|journal=Thesis|via=University of Missouri-Columbia}}</ref> When meat is cured then cold-smoked, the smoke adds [[phenols]] and other chemicals that have an [[antimicrobial]] effect on the meat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pods.dasnr.okstate.edu/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-2055/ANSI-3994web.pdf|title=Meat Curing|last=Ray|first=Frederick|website=Oklahoma State University|publisher=Oklahoma Cooperative Extension Service|access-date=July 24, 2019}}</ref> Hot smoking has less impact on preservation and is primarily used for taste and to slow-cook the meat.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.canr.msu.edu/news/smoking_as_a_food_cooking_method|title=Smoking as a food cooking method|website=MSU Extension|language=en|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref> Interest in [[barbecue]] and smoking is on the rise worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/food/move-over-foie-gras-the-latest-rage-in-paris-is--classic-american-barbecue/2016/01/15/1b3ff700-ba52-11e5-829c-26ffb874a18d_story.html|title=Move over, foie gras: The latest rage in Paris is . . . classic American barbecue|website=Washington Post|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hpba.org/Resources/PressRoom/ID/516/2017-State-of-the-Barbecue-Industry-HPBAs-Consumer-Survey-Reveals-Grilling-and-Barbecuing-Is-a-Growing-Year-Round-Lifestyle|title=2017 State of the Barbecue Industry: HPBA's Consumer Survey Reveals Grilling and Barbecuing Is a Growing, Year-Round Lifestyle > Hearth, Patio & Barbecue Association (HPBA)|website=www.hpba.org|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref>\n\n==Smoking with wood==\n\nGenerally wood is [[Smoking (cooking)|smoked]] using [[hardwood]] or [[Pellet fuel|wood pellets]] made from hardwood, softwood is not recommended due to increased PAH from the resin.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Ezike|first=C.O.|date=2018|title=Hydrocarbons (Pahs) in Hardwood and Softwood - Smoked Fish|url=|journal=Journal of Animal Science|volume=2|issue=1|pages=1012|via=JSTOR}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wideopeneats.com/kind-wood-use-smoking-meat/|title=Every Type of Wood to Use for Smoking Every Type of Meat|last=Mattison|first=Lindsay|date=2018-03-27|website=Wide Open Eats|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> Wood smoke adds [[flavor]], [[aroma]], and helps with [[Food preservation|preservation]].<ref name=\":4\" /> There are two types of smoking: cold smoking generally occurs below {{Convert|90|F|C|abbr=}} and has more preservative value. Hot smoking generally occurs above {{Convert|160|F|C}}.<ref name=\":22\" /> Most woods are [[Wood drying|seasoned]] and not used [[Green wood|green]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bbq.tamu.edu/2016/01/07/seasoned-wood-for-smoking-barbecue/|title=Importance of seasoned wood for smoking barbecue|last=Savell|first=Jeff|date=2016-01-07|website=Texas Barbecue|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-27}}</ref> There are many types of wood used for smoking; a partial list includes:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thespruceeats.com/choose-right-wood-barbecue-smoke-331529|title=Choose the Right Wood for Your Smoker|website=The Spruce Eats|language=en|access-date=2019-07-27}}</ref>\n\n* Woods with a mild flavor: [[Alder]], [[apple]], [[apricot]], [[Fraxinus|ash]], [[birch]], [[cherry]], [[maple]], [[peach]], [[pear]].\n* Woods with a medium flavor: [[Almond]], [[hickory]], [[pecan]], [[Quercus stellata|post oak]], [[Lithocarpus|pasania]].\n* Woods with a strong flavor: [[Acacia]], [[Juglans nigra|black walnut]], [[Prunus virginiana|chokecherry]], [[Vitis|grapevine]], [[mesquite]].\n* Other woods and organic matter: [[Avocado]], [[Laurus nobilis|bay]], [[beech]], [[Juglans cinerea|butternut]], [[Cupaniopsis anacardioides|carrotwood]], [[camphor]], [[castanopsis]], [[chestnut]], [[Thyine wood|citrus woods]], [[Populus|cottonwood]], [[Malus|crabapple]], [[Ficus|fig]], [[guava]], [[Eucalyptus|gum]], [[Celtis|hackberry]], [[Prosopis pallida|kiawe]], [[Syringa vulgaris|lilac]], [[Arbutus|madrone]], [[Morus (plant)|mulberry]], [[olive]], [[peat]], [[plum]], [[persimmon]], [[Allspice|pimento]], [[Camellia sinensis|tea]], and [[willow]].\n\n==Types==\n===African fish smoking===\n[[File:Smoking fish near Dakar, S\u00e9n\u00e9gal (west Africa) (2290515874).jpg|thumb|Smoking fish near Dakar, S\u00e9n\u00e9gal]]\nClose to 80% of all fish caught in most [[African nations]] is [[Smoked fish|smoked]].<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Adeyeye|first=S. A. O.|last2=Oyewole|first2=O. B.|date=2016|title=An Overview of Traditional Fish Smoking In Africa|journal=Journal of Culinary Science & Technology|volume=14|issue=3|pages=198\u2013215|via=JSTOR|doi=10.1080/15428052.2015.1102785}}</ref> Traditionally the processing and smoking of fish has been done by women.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldfishcenter.org/sites/default/files/u24/Annex-26-Guidelines-for-Orientation-and-Training-on-Standards---Processors-and-Traders-Module.pdf|title=Methodologies and Guidelines for Training/ Orientation on Standards to Non-Standards Experts and Cross-Border Trade Compliance|last=|first=|date=|website=World Fish|publisher=World Fish & ARSO|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=August 1, 2019}}</ref> The primary method of smoking is [[Hot-smoking|hot smoking]], the flavor from hot smoking preferred by local consumers.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite journal|last=Tall|first=Amadou|date=5 November 1976|title=OBSTACLES TO THE DEVELOPMENT OF SMALL SCALE FISH TRADE IN WEST AFRICA|url=https://www.oceandocs.org/bitstream/handle/1834/745/Infopeche.pdf?sequence=1|journal=Infopeche|publisher=Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Traditional smoking methods include using bamboo racks over smoky fires, mud ovens and placing the fish directly on smoldering woods and grasses.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":9\" /> Modern methods of smoking include using re-purposed [[oil drums]], [[brick oven]]s, and [[Chorkor oven]]s.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n===American barbecue (smoked)===\n[[File:Smoking Meat.jpg|thumb|American barbecue]]\n{{main|Barbecue}}American [[Barbecue in the United States|barbecue]]'s roots start with the [[Native American cuisine|Native Americans]] who [[smoked fish]] and game to preserve food for leaner times.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bennet|first=M K|date=October 1955|title=The Food Economy of the New England Indians, 1605-75|journal=The Journal of Political Economy|publisher=The University of Chicago Press|volume=LXIII|issue=5|pages=369\u2013397|via=JSTOR}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Driver|first=Harold|last2=Massey|first2=William|date=1957|title=Comparative Studies of North American Indians|journal=Transactions of the American Philosophical Society|publisher=American Philosophical Society|volume=47|issue=2|pages=165 456|doi=10.2307/1005714|jstor=1005714|hdl=2027/mdp.39015000051691|hdl-access=free}}</ref> When [[European colonization of the Americas|Europeans]] first came to North America, they brought with them smoking techniques from Europe and [[Central Asia]] and combined those with the Native American techniques.<ref name=\":22\" /> American barbecue has distinct regional differences: [[North Carolina]] Piedmont style is [[pork shoulder]] with a vinegar & ketchup-based sauce; Eastern style is the whole hog with vinegar & pepper-based sauce; [[South Carolina]] is whole hog or shoulder with a mustard-based sauce; [[Western Tennessee]] and [[Memphis barbeque|Memphis]] are famous for its [[dry rub]] ribs, but wet is also available; [[Kentucky]] is known for their [[mutton]], pork shoulder and whole hog are also very popular; [[Kansas City]] barbecue is more about the [[Barbecue sauce|sauce]], often used with smoked pork, [[lamb and mutton|lamb]], [[chicken]], [[beef]] and [[turkey as food|turkey]]. [[Beef rib]]s, [[Sausage|smoked sausage]], [[Beef brisket|brisket]] are the prevalent meats in Texas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eater.com/2016/6/16/11889444/where-to-eat-barbecue-styles|title=The American Barbecue Regional Style Guide|last=Solares|first=Nick|date=2016-06-16|website=Eater|access-date=2019-07-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://libraries.mercer.edu/ursa/bitstream/handle/10898/1520/Barbecue%20project.pdf;sequence=5|title=Adaptations of Barbecue|last=Bove|first=A.|last2=Drawdy|first2=J.|website=Mercer University|last3=Mitchell|first3=D.|last4=Moye|first4=L.|last5=Thompson|first5=S.|last6=Turnquist|first6=T.|last7=Wagner|authorlink7=M.}}</ref>\n\n===Bacon===\n[[File:American Bacon.jpg|thumb|American \"streaky\" bacon]]\n{{main|Bacon}}Bacon originated with ''petaso'', a Roman version of what is now called bacon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inc.com/john-boitnott/why-bacon-as-a-business-has-no-end-in-sight.html|title=The Bacon Craze Will Never End|last=Boitnott|first=John|date=2014-08-08|website=Inc.com|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> The [[etymology]] of the word ''bacon'' has four possibilities; the [[Old French|Franceis]] word ''bacon'', the [[Old High German|Althochdeutsch]] word ''bahho'', the [[Old Dutch|Old Low Franconian]] word ''baken'', and the [[Proto-Germanic language|Common Germanic]] word ''bakkon''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.englishbreakfastsociety.com/history-of-bacon.html|title=The History of Bacon|last=Bule|first=Guise|date=2018|website=The English Breakfast Society}}</ref> John Harris of [[Calne|Calne, England]], was the first to commercialize production of bacon in the 1770s.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://englishbreakfastsociety.com/history-of-bacon.html|title=History Of Bacon|website=English Breakfast Society|access-date=July 28, 2019}}</ref> Bacon is primarily [[pork]], depending on the type; it can come from the belly, back, loin or side.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rhssilverscribe.org/2459/features/history-of-bacon/|title=History of Bacon|last=Adamson|first=Brynne|website=The Silver Scribe|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> The preparation of bacon varies by type, but most involve [[curing (food preservation)|curing]] and smoking.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://meatscience.org/TheMeatWeEat/topics/processed-meats/article/2017/09/07/bacon---do-you-know-how-it-is-made|title=Bacon - Do you know how it is made?|website=meatscience.org|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> Some of the types of bacon include American ({{a.k.a.}} side bacon or streaky bacon), buckboard (shoulder bacon), Canadian ([[back bacon]]), British and Irish (rasher), Australian (middle bacon), Italian ([[pancetta]]), Hungarian ([[Szalonna (bacon)|szalonna]]), German ([[speck]]), Japanese (beikon), and Slovakian (oravsk\u00e1).<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.oola.com/life-in-flavor/2476027/17-types-of-bacon-you-probably-havent-tried-yet/|title=17 Types of Bacon You Probably Haven't Tried Yet|date=2019-07-03|website=Oola.com|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailymeal.com/travel/ways-bacon-eaten-around-world-0/slide-2|title=Australia from 13 Ways People Eat Bacon Around the World Gallery|website=The Daily Meal|language=en|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> Bacon can also be produced from beef, lamb, and [[wild game]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.therecipe.com/different-kinds-bacon-around-the-world/|title=20 Different Kinds Of Bacon From Around The World|date=2018-11-05|website=TheRecipe|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n\n===Country ham===\n{{main|Country ham}}\n[[File:Country ham.jpg|thumb|Country ham]]\n[[Country ham]] is a popular ham originally developed by [[Thirteen Colonies|American Colonists]] who took traditional Native American fish smoking practices and used them for pork.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1979/09/23/country-hams-well-worth-their-salt-ham-thats-worth-its-salt/5f7d16d1-e7c1-45cb-8416-5d0e9dafe467/|title=The Washington Post|last=Northrop|first=Jo|work=September 23, 1979|access-date=July 25, 2019}}</ref> Country hams traditionally were made in the [[American Southeast]] from [[Virginia]] to [[Missouri]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Rentfrow|first=Greg|last2=Suman|first2=Surendranath|date=2014|title=How to Make a Country Ha|journal=Agriculture and Natural Resources Publications|volume=145|via=JSTOR}}</ref> Most country hams are trimmed, wrapped, [[Cured ham|cured]] in salt, sugar, pepper and various spices. In modern times, some preparations add [[nitrate]]s for [[food safety]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eater.com/2014/10/29/7080059/feature-newsoms-country-hams|title=Ghosts in the Ham House|last=Sula|first=Mike|date=2014-10-29|website=Eater|access-date=2019-07-26}}</ref> After curing the hams are smoked for at least 12 hours, then hung to dry for 9 to 12 months. Some traditional processes can take years from curing to being ready to consume.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Marshall|first=Howard|date=1979|title=Meat Preservation on the Farm in Missouri's \"Little Dixie\"|journal=Journal of American Folklore|volume=92|issue=366|via=JSTOR}}</ref>\n\n===Finnan haddie===\n[[File:FMIB 38894 Smoking Finnan Haddie.jpeg|thumb|Smoking Finnan haddie]]\n{{main|Finnan haddie}}[[Finnan haddie]] is a [[Smoking (cooking)|cold smoked]] [[haddock]] that originated in medieval times in the Scottish village of [[Findon, West Sussex|Findon]].<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Hopley|first=Claire|date=September 1997|title=FINNAN HADDIE|journal=British Heritage|volume=18|issue=6|pages=56|via=EBCO}}</ref> Traditionally the haddock is smoked with [[green wood]] and [[peat]].<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://slowfoodscotland.com/ark-of-taste/|title=Slow Food Scotland - Ark of Taste|language=en|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref> Smoked finnan haddie is the colour of [[straw]], newer commercial methods of drying without smoke produce a  gold or yellow colour.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> Until the 1800s when regular rail service was established, finnan haddie remained a local dish, now it can be found in markets worldwide.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n===Katsuobushi===\n[[File:\u67af\u672c\u80cc\u7bc0 (8517415760).jpg|thumb|Katsuobushi]]\n{{main|Katsuobushi}}[[Katsuobushi]] is a key umami ingredient in [[Japanese cuisine]], among its many uses bonito flakes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://japanology.org/2017/04/the-8-most-important-condiments-and-ingredients-in-japanese-cuisine/|title=The 8 Most Important Condiments and Ingredients in Japanese cuisine|date=2017-04-18|website=Japanology|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> Katsuobushi is made from [[Skipjack tuna|skipjack]] tuna that is washed, quartered smoked with [[oak]], pasania, or castanopsis wood, and cooled repeatedly for a month.<ref>{{Citation|last=Travis Wall|title=Japanology Plus 2016 12 0 Katsuobushi|date=2017-04-28|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MbX9fq5M_pk|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref> Some producers will spray the fish with [[Aspergillus glaucus]] to promote further drying.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hesseltine|first=C. W.|date=1965|title=A Millennium of Fungi, Food, and Fermentation|journal=Mycologia|volume=57|issue=2|pages=149\u2013197|via=JSTOR|doi=10.1080/00275514.1965.12018201}}</ref> After one to 24 months the fish will be katsu (hard) and read for use. To make bonito flakes it is shaved very thin using a Katsuobushi grater box.\n\n===Pastrami===\n[[File:Pastrami by Wise Sons. (14519474073).jpg|thumb|Pastrami]]\n{{main|Pastrami}}[[Pastrami]] is most often made with beef [[brisket]]; it can be made with other cuts of beef.<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite journal|last=Benkerroum|first=Noreddine|title=Traditional Fermented Foods of North African Countries: Technology and Food Safety Challenges With Regard to Microbiological Risks|url=https://www.academia.edu/25785321|journal=Comprehensive Reviews in Food Science and Food Safety|language=en|volume=12|issue=1|pages=54\u201389|issn=1541-4337|doi=10.1111/j.1541-4337.2012.00215.x|year=2013}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite book|title=Umami : unlocking the secrets of the fifth taste|last=Mouritsen, Ole G., author.|isbn=9780231168915|oclc=932317386|date = 2015-01-11}}</ref> The meat is cured in a [[brine]] (most often dry), after drying, it is coated in [[spice]]s and smoked.<ref name=\":12\" /> Smoking can be done by either cold smoking or hot smoking.<ref name=\":12\" /> Pastrami evolved from the [[Huns|Turkish Huns]] who would tenderize and dry meat under their saddles.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nurten|first=Cekal|date=2014|title=Traditional Foods in Turkish Cuisine|journal=The Social Sciences|volume=9|issue=1|pages=1\u20136|via=JSTOR}}</ref> [[Armenians]] saw what the Huns had done and created [[Pastirma|basturma]] that was spiced and air-dried meat.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite journal|last=Durham|first=T. R.|date=2001-02-01|title=Salt, Smoke, and History|url=https://gcfs.ucpress.edu/content/1/1/78|journal=Gastronomica: The Journal of Critical Food Studies|language=en|volume=1|issue=1|pages=78\u201382|issn=1529-3262|doi=10.1525/gfc.2001.1.1.78}}</ref> [[Romanians]] first started brining, spicing, and smoking the beef and created what is now called pastrami.<ref name=\":22\" /> When [[Romanian Jews]] immigrated to the United States, Canada, and Great Britain in the late 1800s, they carried that tradition of pastrami with them.<ref name=\":22\" /> The Romanians that immigrated to the United States, mostly settled in [[New York City]] area and developed the classic New York Pastrami.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://unreachednewyork.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/Romanian-Profile-Final.pdf|title=Romanians in the New York Metro Area|last=All Peoples|first=Initiative|date=July 2009|website=Unreached New York|access-date=July 24, 2019}}</ref> Those that immigrated to Canada mostly settled in [[Montreal]] used a different brining technique and spices and called it [[Montreal-style smoked meat|smoked meat]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Cured, fermented and smoked foods : proceedings of the Oxford Symposium on Food and Cookery 2010|last=Saberi, Helen.|date=2011|publisher=Prospect Books|isbn=9781903018859|oclc=767899626}}</ref> Pastrami is still produced in [[Southwest Asia]] and the [[Middle East]] and is called [[Pastirma|Pastirma, basterma or basturma]].<ref name=\":03\" /> While customarily made with beef, in other regions it can be made with lamb, [[goat]], [[Water buffalo|buffalo]], and [[camel]].<ref name=\":03\" /> [[Corned beef|Corned or salt beef]] uses a similar brine and spices, but is not smoked.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\n===Zhangcha duck===\n[[File:Zhangcha tea smoked duck.jpg|thumb|Zhangcha duck]]\n{{main|Zhangcha duck}}[[Zhangcha duck]] is a dish from [[Sichuan cuisine|Sichuan]] Province in southwestern China made from the Chengdu Ma duck.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unesco.org/new/fileadmin/MULTIMEDIA/HQ/CLT/pdf/CNN_Chengdu_Application_Gastronomy_EN.pdf|title=Chengdu's Application to Join the UNESCO Creative Cities Network as a City of Gastronomy|date=February 2008|website=The United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization}}</ref> The duck is [[Marination|marinated]] in a [[Pickling|pickling liquid]] then smoked with [[Camphorosmeae|camphor]] and tea leaves.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.weiwenku.org/d/104298982|title=Sichuan Cuisine and Snakes \u56db\u5ddd\u83dc\u8207\u5c0f\u5403|website=\u4e2d\u570b\u50b3\u7d71\u6587\u5316\u8a5e\u5f59 (Chinese traditional culture vocabulary)|access-date=27 July 2019}}</ref> After smoking the duck is [[Deep frying|deep fried]], boned and served over [[rice]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Health concerns==\nOne study has shown an association between the frequency of consumption of smoked foods and [[intestinal cancer]].<ref name=\"Fritz\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Fritz | first1 = W. | last2 = So\u00f3s | first2 = K. | title = Smoked food and cancer | journal = Bibliotheca Nutritio et Dieta | volume = 29 | issue = 29 | pages = 57\u201364 | year = 1980 | pmid = 7447916| doi = 10.1159/000387467 | series = Forum of Nutrition | isbn = 978-3-8055-0621-2 }}</ref> However, the study was restricted to a small Slovenian population in Hungary, where the local smoke curing process produces levels of contaminants roughly eight times as high as standard processes elsewhere.<ref name=\"Fritz\" /> Smoked meats have the potential for promoting the growth of ''[[Listeria]]'' bacteria. ''[[Listeria monocytogenes]]'' can also cause serious [[neonatal infection]] and can be [[vertical transmission|transmitted from mother to child]] before or after birth. The infection can cause serious harm or even [[infant mortality|infant death]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Listeria (Listeriosis) |publisher= Centers for Disease Control and Prevention| url = https://www.cdc.gov/listeria/index.html | date= 22 October 2015| accessdate = 2015-12-23}}</ref> The use of soft woods is discouraged, as the resins in softwood increases the concentration of [[polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon]]s (PAHs) that are known carcinogens.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Cooking|Food}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[African longfin eel]]\n* [[Atlantic mackerel]]\n* [[Beef jerky]]\n* [[Black Forest ham]]\n* [[Br\u00e9si]]\n* [[Cod as food|Cod]]\n* [[Cecina (meat)|Cecina]]\n* [[Charcuterie]]\n* [[Deli meat]]\n* [[Gammon (meat)|Gammon]]\n* [[Herring as food|Herring]]\n* [[List of smoked foods]]\n* [[Smoked salmon|Salmon]]\n* [[Suho meso]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{commons category-inline|Smoked meat}}\n* {{Cookbook-inline|Smoking}}\n* [https://www.stevenraichlen.com/programs/project-smoke/ Project Smoke]\n\n{{Meat}}\n\n[[Category:Smoked meat| ]]\n[[Category:Jewish cuisine]]\n[[Category:Louisiana cuisine]]\n[[Category:Cold cut]]\n[[Category:Sandwiches]]\n[[Category:Montreal cuisine]]\n[[Category:Cuisine of Quebec]]\n[[Category:Canadian cuisine]]\n", "name_user": "1980fast", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eKatsuobushi:Grammar; add link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smoked_meat"}
{"title_page": "1. FC Schweinfurt 05", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname    = 1. FC Schweinfurt 05\n| fullname    = 1. Fussball-Club Schweinfurt 1905, Verein f\u00fcr Leibes\u00fcbungen e.V.\n| image       = 1. FC Schweinfurt 05 logo.svg\n| image_size  = 200\n| nickname    = ''Die Schn\u00fcdel'' <br> ''Die Gr\u00fcn-Wei\u00dfen''\n| founded     = {{Start date and years ago|df=yes|1905|5|5}}\n| ground      = [[Willy-Sachs-Stadion]]\n| capacity    = 15,060<ref name=\"Stadion\">{{cite web|title=Schweinfurter DFB-Pokalspiel ausverkauft|trans-title=DFB-Pokal match sold out|publisher=www.bfv.de|url=http://www.bfv.de/cms/spielbetrieb/neuigkeiten/news_archiv_85656_schweinfurter_dfb-pokalspiel_ausverkauft_223856.html|accessdate=10 October 2017|language=German}}</ref> (860 seated)\n| chairman    = Markus Wolf\n| manager     = Tobias Strobl\n| league      = [[Regionalliga Bayern]] (IV)\n| season      = [[2018\u201319 Regionalliga|2018\u201319]]\n| position    = 4th\n| current     = \n| website     = http://www.fcschweinfurt05.de/\n| pattern_la1 =\n| pattern_b1  =\n| pattern_ra1 =\n| pattern_sh1 =\n| pattern_so1 =\n| leftarm1    = 228B22\n| body1       = 228B22\n| rightarm1   = 228B22\n| shorts1     = FFFFFF\n| socks1      = 228B22\n| pattern_la2 =\n| pattern_b2  =\n| pattern_ra2 =\n| pattern_sh2 =\n| pattern_so2 =\n| leftarm2    = 000000\n| body2       = 000000\n| rightarm2   = 000000\n| shorts2     = 000000\n| socks2      = AAFF00\n| pattern_la3 =\n| pattern_b3  =\n| pattern_ra3 =\n| pattern_sh3 =\n| pattern_so3 =\n| leftarm3    =\n| body3       =\n| rightarm3   =\n| shorts3     =\n| socks3      =\n}}\n'''1. Fussball-Club Schweinfurt 1905, Verein f\u00fcr Leibes\u00fcbungen e.V.''', called '''1. FC Schweinfurt 05''',  '''Schweinfurt 05''', or simply '''FC 05''', is a [[football in Germany|German association football club]] established in [[Schweinfurt]] ([[Bavaria]]) in 1905. It has sections for [[netball]], [[fistball]], [[field hockey]], [[badminton]], [[gymnastics]], [[Rugby football|rugby]], [[American football]], [[futsal]], and [[Sport of athletics|athletics]].\n\nThe club is well-known nationally and even internationally due to successful years in top and second tier football leagues from the 1930s to the 1970s. During the late 1930s, Schweinfurt's [[midfielder]]s [[Albin Kitzinger]] and [[Andreas Kupfer]], today considered as two of the best [[Half back (association football)|half-back]] players of all time,<ref name=\"Wunderteam\">{{cite web|title=Breslau Elf Chronicles \u2013 Tale Of A German Wunderteam |publisher=www.thehardtackle.com|url=http://www.thehardtackle.com/2012/breslau-elf-chronicles-tale-of-a-german-wunderteam/ |accessdate=11 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Schnuedel\">{{cite web|title=Eintracht gegen Schweinfurt: Wer sind diese Schn\u00fcdel \u00fcberhaupt? |publisher=www.fnp.de|url=https://www.fnp.de/eintracht-frankfurt/eintracht-gegen-schweinfurt-sind-diese-schnuedel-ueberhaupt-10447715.html|accessdate=27 November 2019|language=German}}</ref> \nformed the core of the [[Germany national football team]] and represented their country at the [[1938 FIFA World Cup]] and within the [[FIFA]] selection [[Europe XI]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Football Association 75th Anniversary Celebration Match: England 3 Rest of Europe 0 |publisher=www.englandfootballonline.com|url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1900-39/1938-39/M0220RoE1938.html |accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1. FC Schweinfurt 05 |publisher=www.schweinfurtfuehrer.de | url=https://www.schweinfurtfuehrer.de/vereine/sportvereine/1-fc-schweinfurt-1905/ |accessdate=19 July 2017|language=German}}</ref>\n\nThe FC 05 first team, which competes in the tier-four [[Regionalliga Bayern]] since the [[2013\u201314 Regionalliga|2013\u201314]] season, is organized within ''1. FC Schweinfurt 1905 Fu\u00dfball GmbH''.<ref name=\"History\">{{cite web|title=1. FC Schweinfurt 05: Geschichte|trans-title=1. FC Schweinfurt 05: History|publisher=www.fcschweinfurt05.de|url=http://www.fcschweinfurt1905.de/geschichte/|accessdate=17 June 2017|language=German}}</ref> The club plays its home games at [[Willy-Sachs-Stadion]] in Schweinfurt.<ref name=\"Willy Sachs Stadion\">{{cite web|title=Willy-Sachs-Stadion Schweinfurt|publisher=www.youtube.de|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QkUqXTzCubo&t=92s/|accessdate=24 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Early years: 1905\u20131931===\n[[File:Schweinfurt 1905 First Team.jpg|thumb|280px|right|1. FC Schweinfurt 05 team in 1905]]\n\nAt a time when football became more and more popular among broad levels of the population, ''1. Fussball-Club Schweinfurt 1905'' was founded on 5 May 1905 by a group of sports enthusiasts. The club's first chairman, Pepi Popp, designed the still unchanged FC 05 crest.<ref name=\"Schweinfurtf\u00fchrer History\"/> \n\nThe new team played in various local leagues until beginning of the [[First World War]]. The home games were held at [[Stadion am Hutrasen|Hutrasen]] south of river [[Main (river)|Main]], the later venue of local competitor [[VfR 07 Schweinfurt]]. In 1919, Schweinfurt 05 had to move to a new court near Ludwigsbr\u00fccke and became member of the tier-one [[Kreisliga Bayern|Kreisliga Nordbayern]], but relegated after its first season. The team attempted a merger with Turngemeinde Schweinfurt von 1848, which lasted from 1921 to 1923, before the two groups parted ways again and the football division became ''1. Fussball-Club Schweinfurt 1905, Verein f\u00fcr Leibes\u00fcbungen e.V.''<ref name=\"History\"/>\n\nWhile FC 05 did not reap the expected benefits from the brief union, it improved dramatically after re-establishing itself as an independent club. Membership grew significantly and a number of new sports departments were formed within the organization. The football team yielded its first fruits in 1927 by winning the Unterfranken Cup championship,<ref name=\"Schweinfurtf\u00fchrer History\">{{cite web|title=Geschichte des FC 05 Schweinfurt | trans-title=FC Schweinfurt 05 History|publisher=www.schweinfurtfuehrer.de | url=https://www.schweinfurtfuehrer.de/geschichte/geschichte-des-fc-05-schweinfurt/ |accessdate=26 July 2017|language=German}}</ref> and in 1931, when it became Kreisliga Unterfranken champion.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kreisliga Bayern 1931|trans-title=1931 Kreisliga Bayern|publisher=fussball-historie.de|url=http://www.fussball-historie.de/Sued/OstkreisII1931.html|accessdate=10 April 2020|language=German}}</ref>\n\n===Years of excellence: 1931\u20131963===\n[[File:Andreas Kupfer and Albin Kitzinger.jpg|thumb|280px|right|[[Andreas Kupfer]] (left) and [[Albin Kitzinger]]]]\n\nSchweinfurt 05 finally gained first class status again with its entry into the [[Bezirksliga Bayern]] in 1931. \nAfter introduction of the [[Gauliga]] system in 1933, the club became member of the top-flight [[Gauliga Bayern]] thanks to finishing 3rd in Bezirksliga Bayern Nord.\nSchweinfurt experienced an era of successful seasons in those years, winning the Gauliga Bayern in [[1938\u201339 Gauliga Bayern|1939]] and [[1941\u201342 Gauliga Bayern|1942]], and qualifying for the [[List of German football champions|German football championship]] round.\n \nIn the German football championship [[1939 German football championship|1939]] competition, the team barely missed the semi-final qualification games after 3 wins in the group stage, where it defeated later [[1943 German football championship|1943]] and [[1944 German football championship|1944]] German champion [[Dresdner SC]] 1\u20130 in the first leg, but then lost to Dresden 0\u20131 in the deceisive away match.<ref name=\"Stumpf\">{{cite web|title=Ehemaliger 05-Torwart Hans Stumpf gestorben|trans-title=Former 05 goalkeeper Hans Stumpf passed|publisher=mainpost.de|url=https://www.mainpost.de/sport/schweinfurt/Ehemaliger-05-Torwart-Hans-Stumpf-gestorben;art795,5487291?wt_ref=https%3A%2F%2Fde.wikipedia.org%2F&wt_t=1585256396531|accessdate=26 March 2020|language=German}}</ref>\nThe club failed in the round of 16 of the [[1942 German football championship|1942]] German football championship after a 1\u20132 loss to [[SG SS Stra\u00dfburg]].\n\nSchweinfurt made a semi-final appearance in the [[1936 Tschammerpokal]], when it was defeated 2\u20133 by [[FC Schalke 04]], the closest it ever came to winning a national title. Again in 1936, the club moved into its newly constructed stadium, the [[Willy-Sachs-Stadion]], a donation by local [[ZF Sachs|industrialist]] and patron [[Willy Sachs]].<ref name=\"Cicero\">{{cite web|title=Der braune Schatten|trans-title=The brown shadow|publisher=cicero.de|url=http://cicero.de/wirtschaft/der-braune-schatten/37229|accessdate=25 July 2017|language=German}}</ref>\n\nAt that time, FC 05 midfielders [[Albin Kitzinger]] and [[Andreas Kupfer|Andreas 'Ander' Kupfer]] became renowned in international football as they formed one of the best half-back duos in Europe. Kitzinger and Kupfer were an essential part of the famous [[Breslau Eleven|Germany national team]] who defeated [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] 8\u20130 in [[Wroc\u0142aw|Breslau]] ([[Poland]]) on 16 May 1937.<ref name=\"Wunderteam\"/> One year later they competed at the [[1938 FIFA World Cup]], and were both called up to represent Germany within the FIFA selection [[Europe XI]] in the [[The Football Association|FA]] 75th anniversary game against [[England national football team|England]] at [[Highbury Stadium|Highbury]] in [[London]].\n\nDue to the [[Second World War]], Schweinfurt 05 merged with Luftwaffen SV Schweinfurt into KSG Schweinfurt for the [[1943\u201344 Gauliga Bayern|1943\u201344]] and [[1944\u201345 Gauliga Bayern|1944\u201345]] Gauliga seasons.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gauligisten| trans-title=Gauliga clubs|publisher=www.deutscherfussball.info | url=https://www.deutscherfussball.info/Gauligisten-S-d--Sa_Se.htm |accessdate=24 August 2017}}</ref> The club temporarily had been dissolved in May 1945 under pressure from the occupying powers.<ref name=\"Schweinfurtf\u00fchrer History\"/>\n\nAfter World War II, the re-established 1. FC Schweinfurt 05 was integrated into the first tier [[Oberliga S\u00fcd (1945\u201363)|Oberliga S\u00fcd]], which, for the first time in German football, introduced the system of contract players in August 1948.<ref>{{cite web|title=Der lange Weg zum Profi| trans-title=The long road to professional football|publisher=www.bpb.de | url=https://www.bpb.de/gesellschaft/medien-und-sport/bundesliga/160779/geschichte-der-bundesliga?p=1 |accessdate=11 April 2020|language=German}}</ref>  \nThe club stayed in the Oberliga for the duration of the league's existence until the [[Bundesliga]], Germany's new professional league, was founded in 1963. \nSchweinfurt reached the round of the last sixteen of the [[DFB-Pokal 1954\u201355|1954\u201355]] DFB-Pokal, where it lost 0\u20131 in the replay against FC Schalke 04 after a 1\u20131 draw in the first match.\nOn the occasion of the club's 50th anniversary in 1955, Schweinfurt could demonstrate its level when the team defeated German champion [[Rot-Weiss Essen]] 3\u20131, and achieved a 1\u20131 draw against [[Everton F.C.]] from English [[Football League First Division]].<ref name=\"Schweinfurtf\u00fchrer History\"/>\n\nIn 1950, Andreas Kupfer became the first [[Captain (sports)|captain]] of the [[West Germany]] national football team in his very final [[List of Germany international footballers|44th]] appearance. FC 05 goalkeeper [[G\u00fcnter Bernard]] made two West Germany appearances in 1962, before he joined Bundesliga founding member [[SV Werder Bremen]] one year later, and was named in Germany's squad for the [[1966 FIFA World Cup]].\n\n===Second tier years: 1963\u20131976===\nAs it did not qualify for the newly established Bundesliga in 1963, Schweinfurt 05 found itself playing in the second tier [[Regionalliga S\u00fcd (1963\u20131974)|Regionalliga S\u00fcd]]. In the [[1965\u201366 Regionalliga|1965\u201366]] season, the club became Southern German champion and made it to the [[1965\u201366 Regionalliga#Bundesliga promotion round|Bundesliga advancement games]], but was unable to ascend to the top tier.\n\nWith the introduction of the [[2. Bundesliga]] in 1974, Schweinfurt was founding member of the [[2. Bundesliga S\u00fcd (1974\u201381)|southern division]] despite only finishing 15th in the last Regionalliga year. For its first 2. Bundesliga season in [[1974\u201375 2. Bundesliga|1974\u201375]], the club had signed-up former national team [[forward (association football)|striker]] and [[List of Bundesliga top scorers|Bundesliga top scorer]] [[Lothar Emmerich]]. The team earned an excellent third place and barely missed the advancement games for promotion to Bundesliga.\n\n===Yo-yo years: 1976\u20132016===\n[[File:Schweinfurt Performance Chart.png|280px|thumb|Historical chart of the 1. FC Schweinfurt 05 league performance after 1945]]\nAfter the 1974\u201375 season, FC 05 began to falter: poor results and financial problems saw the club descend first to the [[Bayernliga]] (III) and then, for the first time in 1983, to the [[Landesliga Bayern-Nord]] (IV). \nSchweinfurt 05 became a [[yo-yo club]] ascending and descending between tiers III and IV, with just a pair of brief 2. Bundesliga appearances in [[1990\u201391 2. Bundesliga|1990\u201391]] and in [[2001\u201302 2. Bundesliga|2001\u201302]]. \n\nAs 1989\u201390 Bayernliga champion the club prevailed in the advancement games to 2. Bundesliga, but was not able to keep pace in the new league. \nIn 2001, Schweinfurt qualified for promotion to 2. Bundesliga after finishing 3rd in [[2000\u201301 Regionalliga|Regionalliga S\u00fcd]]. \nDespite of a decent first half of the tier-two season, the team finally could not avoid relegation after one year.\nThe club made it into the last sixteen of the [[1989\u201390 DFB-Pokal]], where it lost 0\u20132 to [[Eintracht Braunschweig]].\n\nDisasters happened in 2004 when FC Schweinfurt 05 was forced to leave the Regionalliga S\u00fcd (III) because of financial reasons, and in 2005 when the club went bankrupt. The results in the Bayernliga (IV) were annulled, and the team was relegated to the fifth tier Landesliga.\n\nA re-structured club successfully worked its way back into Bayernliga in 2008. After it was relegated again to the Landesliga in 2009, the team returned to the Bayerliga immediately the following year. At the end of the [[2011\u201312 Bayernliga|2011\u201312]] season the club managed to qualify for the promotion round to the new [[Regionalliga Bayern]] (IV) and advanced to the second round, where the club missed out on promotion.<ref>{{cite web|title=Das war die Relegation 2012 auf Verbandsebene |publisher=www.fupa.net|url=http://www.fupa.net/berichte/so-laeuft-die-relegation-auf-verbandsebene-21714.html |accessdate=13 June 2017|language=German}}</ref>\nThe club finally earned direct promotion to tier-four Regionalliga Bayern in the [[2012\u201313 Bayernliga|2012\u201313]] season by taking the championship in the Bayernliga northern division.\nSchweinfurt's first three Regionalliga years, however, were characterized by a permanent struggle against relegation.\n\n===Recent years: 2016\u2013today===\n[[File:2018-08-17 1. FC Schweinfurt 05 vs. FC Schalke 04 (DFB-Pokal) by Sandro Halank\u2013100.jpg|thumb|280px|[[2018\u201319 DFB-Pokal]]: [[Nabil Bentaleb]] ([[FC Schalke 04]]) and [[Adam Jabiri]] (FC Schweinfurt 05)]]\nIn 2016, the FC 05 first team was spun off into ''1. FC Schweinfurt 1905 Fu\u00dfball GmbH''. By means of the reorganization, the club again established professional structures that shall pave the way back to higher leagues.<ref name=\"History\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Legende: 1. FC Schweinfurt 05|trans-title=A legend: 1. FC Schweinfurt 05|url=http://www.zeitspiel-magazin.de/legende-1-fc-schweinfurt-05.html|publisher=zeitspiel-magazin.de|language=German|accessdate=2018-08-23}}</ref>\n\nSchweinfurt actually experienced an upturn in the [[2016\u201317 Regionalliga#Regionalliga Bayern|2016\u201317]] season and finished 8th in Regionalliga Bayern. In addition, the team succeeded in winning the [[Bavarian Cup]] after a 1\u20130 victory over [[SV Wacker Burghausen]] in the final, combined with qualification for the [[2017\u201318 DFB-Pokal]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Schweinfurt 05 gewinnt den Toto-Pokal 2017|trans-title=Schweinfurt 05 has won the 2017 Toto Cup|publisher=bfv.de|url=http://www.bfv.de/cms/spielbetrieb/neuigkeiten/2017_205893_schweinfurt_gewinnt_den_toto-pokal_2017_215550.html|accessdate=27 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2017\u201318 Regionalliga#Regionalliga Bayern|2017\u201318]] Regionalliga, Schweinfurt's ambitioned team was not able to jeopardize the championship of [[TSV 1860 M\u00fcnchen]], which had been relegated directly from 2. Bundesliga to Regionalliga Bayern after the [[2016\u201317 2. Bundesliga|2016\u201317]] season due to a missing license for [[3. Liga]]. The club finally finished 3rd, where striker [[Adam Jabiri]] became 2017\u201318 Regionalliga Bayern top scorer (28 goals). \n1. FC Schweinfurt 05 defeated 2. Bundesliga club [[SV Sandhausen]] 2\u20131 in the 2017\u201318 DFB-Pokal first round,<ref>{{cite web|title=DFB-Pokal, 2017/2018, 1. Runde|publisher=www.dfb.de|url=https://www.dfb.de/dfb-pokal/spieltag/?spieledb_path=%2Fmatches%2F2247860 |accessdate=14 August 2017}}</ref> but then lost 0\u20134 to later [[2018 DFB-Pokal Final|cup winner]] [[SG Eintracht Frankfurt]].<ref>{{cite web|title=DFB-Pokal, 2017/2018, 2. Runde|publisher=www.dfb.de|url=https://www.dfb.de/dfb-pokal/spieltag/?spieledb_path=%2Fmatches%2F2249085 |accessdate=25 October 2017|language=German}}</ref>\nIn the same season, Schweinfurt 05 successfully defended the [[2017\u201318 Verbandspokal|Bavarian Cup]] after a 3\u20131 victory over league competitor [[SpVgg Oberfranken Bayreuth]] in the final, and qualified for the [[2018\u201319 DFB-Pokal]].\n\nWith the objective of the [[2018\u201319 Regionalliga#Regionalliga Bayern|2018\u201319 Regionalliga]] championship and promotion to 3. Liga, Schweinfurt signed up former [[2009 UEFA European Under-17 Championship|European U-17 Champion]] [[Florian Trinks]]. \nHowever, the club clearly missed the chance for promotion and finished 4th end of this season.\nIn the 2018\u201319 DFB-Pokal first round, Schweinfurt lost 0\u20132 to [[2017\u201318 Bundesliga|previous season's Bundesliga runner-up]] and [[2018\u201319 UEFA Champions League]] competitor [[FC Schalke 04]].<ref>{{cite web|title=DFB-Pokal, 2018/2019, 1. Runde|publisher=www.dfb.de|url=https://www.dfb.de/dfb-pokal/spieltag/?no_cache=1&spieledb_path=%2Fmatches%2F2261348 |accessdate=18 August 2018|language=German}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=DFB Cup Men: 1. FC Schweinfurt 05 vs. FC Schalke 04 |publisher=tv.dfb.de|url=https://tv.dfb.de/video/dfb-cup-men-1-fc-schweinfurt-05-vs-fc-schalke-04/22518/ |accessdate=18 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n===League===\n* '''[[Gauliga Bayern]]''' (I)\n** '''Champions''': (2) [[1938\u201339 Gauliga Bayern|1938\u201339]], [[1941\u201342 Gauliga Bayern|1941\u201342]]\n** ''Runners-up'': (2) [[1936\u201337 Gauliga Bayern|1936\u201337]], [[1942\u201343 Gauliga Bayern|1942\u201343]]<sup>\u2020</sup>\n* '''[[Regionalliga S\u00fcd (1963\u20131974)|Regionalliga S\u00fcd]]''' (II)* (III)**\n** '''Champions''': [[1965\u201366 Regionalliga|1965\u201366]]*\n** ''Third'': [[2000\u201301 Regionalliga|2000\u201301]]**<sup>\u2021</sup>\n* '''[[Bayernliga]]''' (III)* (IV)**\n** '''Champions''': (2) 1989\u201390*<sup>\u2021</sup>, 1997\u201398**\n** ''Runners-up'': (2) 1981\u201382*, 1988\u201389*\n* '''[[Bayernliga|Bayernliga Nord]]''' (V)\n** '''Champions''': 2012\u201313\n* '''[[Landesliga Bayern-Nord]]''' (IV)* (V)** (VI)***\n** '''Champions''': (3) 1983\u201384*, 1985\u201386*, 2006\u201307**\n** ''Runners-up'': 2009\u201310***\n* '''[[Landesliga Bayern-Nordwest]]''' (VI)\n** '''Champions''': 2016\u201317<sup>#</sup>\n===Youth===\n* '''[[Bavarian Under 19 championship]]'''\n** '''Winners''': 2001\n** ''Runners-up'': (3) 1961, 1966, 1968\n* '''[[Bavarian Under 17 championship]]'''\n** '''Winners''': 2005\n** ''Runners-up'': 1995\n* '''[[Bavarian Under 15 championship]]'''\n** '''Winners''': 2003\n** ''Runners-up'': (2) 1986, 1994\n{{col-2}}\n===Cup===\n* '''[[DFB-Pokal]]'''\n** ''Semi-finals'': [[Tschammerpokal 1936|1936]]\n** ''Last sixteen'': (2) [[DFB-Pokal 1954\u201355|1954\u201355]], [[DFB-Pokal 1989\u201390|1989\u201390]]\n* '''Southern German Cup'''\n** '' Runners-up'': (3) 1933, 1957, 1958\n* '''[[Bavarian Cup]]'''\n** '''Winners''': (3) 1933, [[2016\u201317 Verbandspokal|2016\u201317]], [[2017\u201318 Verbandspokal|2017\u201318]]\n* '''[[Bavarian Cup#Regional winners|Unterfranken Cup]]'''\n** '''Winners''': (5) 1927, 1963<sup>#</sup>, 1996, [[2006 Bavarian Cup|2006]], [[2009 Bavarian Cup|2009]]\n<br>\n<sup>\u2020</sup> Northern division <br> <sup>\u2021</sup> Promoted to [[2001\u201302 2. Bundesliga|2. Bundesliga]] <br> <sup>#</sup> Reserve team\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Seasons==\n===First team===\nThe season-by-season performance of the club from 1931 until today:<ref>{{cite web|title=Das deutsche Fu\u00dfball-Archiv | trans-title=Historical German domestic league tables|publisher=www.f-archiv.de | url=http://www.f-archiv.de/ |accessdate=13 June 2017|language=German}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Fussball.de&nbsp;\u2013 Ergebnisse | trans-title=Tables and results of all German football leagues|publisher=www.fussball.de | url=http://www.fussball.de/fussball-ergebnisse-die-top-ligen-bei-fussball-de/id_45692854/index |accessdate=13 June 2017|language=German}}</ref>\n\n{| border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=2>\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#dfdfdf\"\n| '''Season'''\n| '''Division'''\n| '''[[Bavarian football league system|Tier]]'''\n| '''Position'''\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 1931\u201332\n| align=\"left\"| [[Bezirksliga Bayern | Bezirksliga Bayern (Nord)]]\n| rowspan=32| I\n| 4th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 1932\u201333\n| align=\"left\"| Bezirksliga Bayern (Nord)\n| 3rd\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1933\u201334 Gauliga Bayern|1933\u201334]]\n| align=\"left\"| [[Gauliga Bayern]]\n| 4th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1934\u201335 Gauliga Bayern|1934\u201335]]\n| align=\"left\"| Gauliga Bayern\n| 3rd\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1935\u201336 Gauliga Bayern|1935\u201336]]\n| align=\"left\"| Gauliga Bayern\n| 4th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1936\u201337 Gauliga Bayern|1936\u201337]]\n| align=\"left\"| Gauliga Bayern\n| 2nd\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1937\u201338 Gauliga Bayern|1937\u201338]]\n| align=\"left\"| Gauliga Bayern\n| 7th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1938\u201339 Gauliga Bayern|1938\u201339]]\n| align=\"left\"| Gauliga Bayern\n| 1st\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1939\u201340 Gauliga Bayern|1939\u201340]]\n| align=\"left\"| Gauliga Bayern\n| 3rd\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1940\u201341 Gauliga Bayern|1940\u201341]]\n| align=\"left\"| Gauliga Bayern\n| 7th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1941\u201342 Gauliga Bayern|1941\u201342]]\n| align=\"left\"| Gauliga Bayern\n| 1st\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1942\u201343 Gauliga Bayern|1942\u201343]]\n| align=\"left\"| Gauliga Nordbayern\n| 2nd\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1943\u201344 Gauliga Bayern|1943\u201344]]\n| align=\"left\"| Gauliga Nordbayern\n| 5th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1944\u201345 Gauliga Bayern|1944\u201345]]\n| align=\"left\"| Gauliga Bayern\n| ''no results''\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1945\u201346 Oberliga|1945\u201346]]\n| align=\"left\"| [[Oberliga S\u00fcd (1945\u201363)|Oberliga S\u00fcd]]\n| 7th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1946\u201347 Oberliga|1946\u201347]]\n| align=\"left\"| Oberliga S\u00fcd\n| 9th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1947\u201348 Oberliga|1947\u201348]]\n| align=\"left\"| Oberliga S\u00fcd\n| 13th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1948\u201349 Oberliga|1948\u201349]]\n| align=\"left\"| Oberliga S\u00fcd\n| 10th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1949\u201350 Oberliga|1949\u201350]]\n| align=\"left\"| Oberliga S\u00fcd\n| 12th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1950\u201351 Oberliga|1950\u201351]]\n| align=\"left\"| Oberliga S\u00fcd\n| 7th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1951\u201352 Oberliga|1951\u201352]]\n| align=\"left\"| Oberliga S\u00fcd\n| 14th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1952\u201353 Oberliga|1952\u201353]]\n| align=\"left\"| Oberliga S\u00fcd\n| 5th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1953\u201354 Oberliga|1953\u201354]]\n| align=\"left\"| Oberliga S\u00fcd\n| 8th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1954\u201355 Oberliga|1954\u201355]]\n| align=\"left\"| Oberliga S\u00fcd\n| 3rd\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1955\u201356 Oberliga|1955\u201356]]\n| align=\"left\"| Oberliga S\u00fcd\n| 8th\n|- align=\"center\"\n|| [[1956\u201357 Oberliga|1956\u201357]]\n| align=\"left\"| Oberliga S\u00fcd\n| 12th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1957\u201358 Oberliga|1957\u201358]]\n| align=\"left\"| Oberliga S\u00fcd\n| 8th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1958\u201359 Oberliga|1958\u201359]]\n| align=\"left\"| Oberliga S\u00fcd\n| 10th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1959\u201360 Oberliga|1959\u201360]]\n| align=\"left\"| Oberliga S\u00fcd\n| 12th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1960\u201361 Oberliga|1960\u201361]]\n| align=\"left\"| Oberliga S\u00fcd\n| 14th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[1961\u201362 Oberliga|1961\u201362]]\n| align=\"left\"| Oberliga S\u00fcd\n| 14th\n|- align=\"center\"\n|| [[1962\u201363 Oberliga|1962\u201363]]\n| align=\"left\"| Oberliga S\u00fcd\n| 11th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 1963\u201364\n| align=\"left\"| [[Regionalliga S\u00fcd (1963\u20131974)|Regionalliga S\u00fcd]]\n| rowspan=13| II\n| 7th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 1964\u201365\n| align=\"left\"| Regionalliga S\u00fcd\n| 15th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 1965\u201366\n| align=\"left\"| Regionalliga S\u00fcd\n| 1st\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 1966\u201367\n| align=\"left\"| Regionalliga S\u00fcd\n| 10th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 1967\u201368\n| align=\"left\"| Regionalliga S\u00fcd\n| 5th\n|- align=\"center\"\n| 1968\u201369\n| align